Volatile Organic Compounds

A more practical and generic evaluation of the dissolution properties of a larger group of solvents is instead provided by the so-called Hansen method, which is inspired by the well-known “like-dissolves-like” approach37. The Hansen method separates the total cohesion energy (per molar volume) of a solvent into three Hansen solubility parameters (HSPs): (i) the dispersion energy that considers molecular dispersion interactions (δD); (ii) the polar energy that considers molecular dipolar interactions (δP); and (iii) the hydrogen-bonding energy that considers molecular hydrogen bonding interactions (δH). The similarity in solubility capacity of two solvents is provided by their proximity in the 3D Hansen solubility space, with their effective separation (Ra) being calculated with the following equation:1Ra2=4δD1−δD22+δP1−δP22+δH1−δH22\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
